# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: benjamin-apthorp-gould
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The oldest city in New York, the City of Albany is the economic and cultural core of New York State's Capital District.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Capital District is a metropolitan area including the nearby cities and suburbs of Colonie, Troy, Schenectady, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] With an estimated 1.3 million residents, the Capital District is one of the most populous metropolitan areas and is the fastest-growing region in Upstate New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The area that ultimately became Albany was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The area was settled by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau in 1614 for fur trading and Fort Orange in 1624.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1664, the English took over the Dutch settlements, renaming the city "Albany" in honor of the Scottish title of the Duke of York (later James II of England and Ireland and James VII of Scotland): the Duke of Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city was officially chartered in 1686 under English rule.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It became the capital of New York in 1797 after the formation of the United States.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the oldest surviving settlement of the original British Thirteen Colonies north of Virginia.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th century and throughout most of the 19th, Albany was a center of trade and transportation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city lies toward the north end of the navigable Hudson River.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It was the original eastern terminus of the Erie Canal and was home to some of the earliest railroads in the world.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1920s, a powerful political machine controlled by the Democratic Party emerged in Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's population shrank because of urban sprawl and suburbanization in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1990s, the New York State Legislature approved for the city a US$234 million building and renovation plan, which spurred downtown redevelopment.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2020, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward artificial intelligence, AI-based photonics, quantum computing hardware manufacturing, nanotechnology, and digital electronics.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Hudson River area was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans, who called it *Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw*, meaning "the fireplace of the Mohican nation".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Based to the west along the Mohawk River, the Iroquoian-speaking Mohawk called it *skahnéhtati*, also transliterated to Sche-negh-ta-da, "through the pine woods", referring to the path they took there.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] According to Hendrick Aupaumut, the Mohicans came to the area from the north and the west.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] They settled along the Mahicannituck River, which is now called the Hudson River, and called themselves the *Muh-he-con-neok*, the "People of the Waters That Are Never Still".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawks, one of the Five Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy, were based in the Mohawk valley and noted for their fur trading and their access to trade between the Iroquois and other nations.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawk became strong trading partners with the Dutch and English.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It is likely that the area was visited by European fur traders perhaps as early as 1540, but the extent and duration of those visits are unclear.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Permanent European claims began when Englishman Henry Hudson, exploring for the Dutch East India Company on the *Half Moon* (Dutch: *Halve Maen*), reached the area in 1609, claiming it for the United Netherlands.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1614, Hendrick Christiaensen built Fort Nassau on Castle Island (now called Port of Albany), in the Hudson River.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The fort acted as a fur-trading post and was the first documented European structure in present-day Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Commencement of the fur trade provoked hostility from the French colony in Canada and among the natives, all of whom vied to control the trade.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1618, a flood ruined Fort Nassau, but the Dutch replaced it with Fort Orange on the mainland in 1624.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Both forts were named in honor of the leading family of the Dutch Revolt, members of the House of Orange-Nassau.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Fort Orange and the surrounding area were incorporated as the village of Beverwijck (English: Beaverwick or Beaver District) in 1652, and the city of Albany in 1686.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In these early decades of trade, the Dutch, Mohican, and Mohawk developed relations that reflected differences among their three cultures.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is one of the oldest surviving European settlements from the original Thirteen Colonies and the longest continuously chartered city in the United States.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] When New Netherland was captured by the English in 1664, the name was changed from *Beverwijck* to *Albany* in honor of Prince James, Duke of Albany (later King James VII/II).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Duke of Albany was a Scottish title given since 1398, generally to a younger son of the King of Scots.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The name is ultimately derived from *Alba*, the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Dutch briefly regained Albany in August 1673 and renamed the city *Willemstadt*; the English took permanent possession in 1674 with the Treaty of Westminster.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was formally chartered as a municipality by provincial Governor Thomas Dongan on July 22, 1686.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Dongan Charter was virtually identical in content to the charter awarded to the city of New York three months earlier.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Dongan created Albany as a strip of land 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 16 miles (26 km) long.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Over the years Albany would lose much of the land to the west and annex land to the north and south.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] At this point, Albany had a population of about 500 people.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1754, representatives of seven British North American colonies met in the *Stadt Huys*, Albany's city hall, for the Albany Congress; Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania presented the Albany Plan of Union there, which was the first formal proposal to unite the colonies.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Although it was never adopted by Parliament, it was an important precursor to the United States Constitution.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The same year, the French and Indian War, the fourth in a series of wars dating back to 1689, began.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It ended in 1763 with French defeat, resolving a situation that had been a constant threat to Albany and held back its growth.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Tories and prisoners of war were often jailed in the *Stadt Huys* alongside common criminals.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1776, Albany native Philip Livingston signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] During and after the Revolutionary War, Albany County saw a great increase in real estate transactions.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] After the 1777 colonial victory at the Battle of Saratoga, the upper Hudson Valley was generally at peace as the war raged on elsewhere.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Prosperity was soon seen all over Upstate New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Migrants from Vermont and Connecticut began flowing in, noting the advantages of living on the Hudson and trading at Albany, while being only a few days' sail from New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany reported a population of 3,498 in the first national census in 1790, an increase of almost 700% since its chartering.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] On November 17, 1793, fire broke out at a stable belonging to Leonard Gansevoort, destroying 26 homes on Broadway, Maiden Lane, James Street, and State Street.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Three were arrested and charged with arson: Pompey, a man belonging to Matthew Visscher; Dinah, a 14-year-old girl belonging to Volkert P.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Douw; and Bet, a 12-year-old girl belonging to Philip S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] On January 6, 1794, the three were sentenced to death.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Governor George Clinton issued a temporary stay of execution, but Dinah and Bet were executed by hanging on March 14, and Pompey on April 11, 1794.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1797, the state capital was moved permanently to Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] From statehood to this date, the Legislature had frequently moved the state capital between Albany, Kingston, Poughkeepsie, and the city of New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the tenth-oldest state capital in the United States and the second-oldest city that is a state capital, after Santa Fe, New Mexico.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany has been a center of transportation for much of its history.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Albany saw development of the turnpike and by 1815, Albany was the turnpike center of the state.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The development of Simeon De Witt's gridded block system in 1794—which renamed streets that had originally named after the British royal family with names of birds and mammals instead—was intersected by these major arterials coming out of Albany, cutting through the city at unexpected angles.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The construction of the turnpike, in conjunction with canal and railroad systems, made Albany the hub of transportation for pioneers going to Buffalo and the Michigan Territory in the early and mid-19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1807, Robert Fulton initiated a steamboat line from New York City to Albany, the first successful enterprise of its kind anywhere in the world.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] By 1810, with 10,763 people, Albany was the tenth-largest urban place in the nation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The town and village north of Albany known as "the Colonie" was annexed in 1815.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1825 the Erie Canal was completed, forming a continuous water route from the Great Lakes to New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Unlike the current Barge Canal, which ends at nearby Waterford, the original Erie Canal ended at Albany; Lock 1 was north of Colonie Street.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Canal emptied into a 32-acre (13 ha) man-made lagoon called the Albany Basin, which was Albany's main port from 1825 until the Port of Albany-Rensselaer opened in 1932.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1829, while working as a professor at the Albany Academy, Joseph Henry, widely regarded as "the foremost American scientist of the 19th century", built the first electric motor.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Three years later, he discovered electromagnetic self-induction (the SI unit for which is now the henry).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] He went on to be the first Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1830 and 1840 censuses, Albany was ranked as the ninth-largest urban place in the nation; it dropped back to tenth in 1850.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] This was the last time the city was one of the top ten largest urban places in the nation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany also has significant history with rail transport, as the location of two major regional railroad headquarters.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Delaware and Hudson Railway was headquartered in Albany at what is now the SUNY System Administration Building.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1853, Erastus Corning, a noted industrialist and Albany's mayor from 1834 to 1837, consolidated ten railroads stretching from Albany to Buffalo into the New York Central Railroad (NYCRR), headquartered in Albany until Cornelius Vanderbilt moved it to New York City in 1867.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] One of the ten companies that formed the NYCRR was the Mohawk and Hudson Railroad, which was the first railroad in the state and the first successful steam railroad running regularly scheduled service in the country.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] While the key to Albany's economic prosperity in the 19th century was transportation, industry and business also played a role.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Largely thanks to the city's Dutch and German roots, beer was one of its biggest commodities.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Beverwyck Brewery, originally known as Quinn and Nolan (Nolan being mayor of Albany 1878–1883), was the last remaining brewer from that time when it closed in 1972.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city's location at the east end of the Erie Canal gave it unparalleled access to both raw products and a captive customer base in the west.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was known for its publishing houses, and to some extent, still is.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was second only to Boston in the number of books produced for most of the 19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Iron foundries in both the north and south ends of the city attracted thousands of immigrants to the city for industrial jobs.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Intricate wrought-iron details constructed in those years remain visible on what are now historic buildings.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The iron industry waned by the 1890s due to increased costs associated with a newly unionized workforce and the opening of mines in the Mesabi Range in Minnesota.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's other major exports during the 18th and 19th centuries were furs, wheat, meat, and lumber.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] By 1865, there were almost 4,000 saw mills in the Albany area and the Albany Lumber District was the largest lumber market in the nation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city was also home to a number of banks.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Bank of Albany (1792–1861) was the second chartered bank in New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city was the original home of the Albank (founded in 1820 as the Albany Savings Bank), KeyBank (founded in 1825 as the Commercial Bank of Albany), and Norstar Bank (founded as the State Bank of Albany in 1803).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] American Express was founded in Albany in 1850 as an express mail business.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1871, the northwestern portion of Albany—west from Magazine Street—was annexed to the neighboring town of Guilderland after the town of Watervliet refused annexation of the territory.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In return for this loss, portions of Bethlehem and Watervliet were added to Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Part of the land annexed to Guilderland was ceded back to Albany in 1910, setting up the current western border.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The train carrying the body of slain President Abraham Lincoln came through Albany on the way to Illinois and the ghostly image of that train remains.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany opened one of the first commercial airports in the world, and the first municipal airport in the United States, in 1908.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Originally on a polo field on Loudon Road, it moved to Westerlo Island in 1909 and remained there until 1928.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Albany Municipal Airport—jointly owned by the city and county—was moved to its current location in Colonie in 1928.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] By 1916 Albany's northern and southern borders reached their modern courses; Westerlo Island, to the south, became the second-to-last annexation, which occurred in 1926.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Erastus Corning 2nd, arguably Albany's most notable mayor (and great-grandson of the former mayor of the same name), was elected in 1941.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] While Corning brought stability to the office of mayor, it is said even those who admire him greatly cannot come up with a sizable list of "major concrete Corning achievements." Corning is given credit for saving—albeit somewhat unintentionally—much of Albany's historic architecture.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, a time when federal aid for urban renewal was plentiful, Albany did not have growth in its economy or infrastructure.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It lost more than 20 percent of its population during the Corning years, as people moved to newer housing in the suburbs, followed by most of the downtown businesses moving there as well.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] While cities across the country grappled with similar issues, the problems were magnified in Albany: interference from the Democratic political machine hindered progress considerably.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 1960, the mayor sold the city's stake in the airport to the county, citing budget issues.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It was known from then on as Albany County Airport until a massive upgrade and modernization project between 1996 and 1998, when it was rebranded Albany International Airport.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Governor Nelson Rockefeller (1959–1973) (R) tried to stimulate the city with new monumental architecture and large, government-sponsored building projects; he drove construction of the Empire State Plaza, SUNY Albany's uptown campus, and much of the W.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany County Republican Chairman Joseph C.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Frangella once quipped, "Governor Rockefeller was the best mayor Albany ever had." Corning, although opposed to the project, was responsible for negotiating the payment plan for the Empire State Plaza.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Rockefeller did not want to be limited by the Legislature's power of the purse, so Corning devised a plan to have the county pay for the construction and have the state sign a lease-ownership agreement.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The state paid off the bonds until 2004.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It was Rockefeller's only viable option, and he agreed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the clout Corning gained from the situation, he gained inclusion of the State Museum, a convention center, and a restaurant, back in the plans—ideas which Rockefeller had originally vetoed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The county gained $35 million in fees and the city received $13 million for lost tax revenue.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Having the state offices in the city enabled it to keep good jobs and retain middle-class residents.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Another major project of the 1960s and 1970s was the construction of Interstate 787 and the South Mall Arterial.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] A proposed Mid-Crosstown Arterial never came to fruition.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] One of the project's main results was separating the city from the Hudson River.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] When Corning died in 1983, Thomas Whalen assumed the mayorship and was reelected twice.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] He encouraged redevelopment of historic structures and helped attract federal dollars earmarked for that purpose.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] What Corning had saved from destruction, Whalen refurbished for continued and new uses.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Mayor's Office of Special Events was created in an effort to increase the number of festivals and artistic events in the city, including a year-long *Dongan Charter* tricentennial celebration in 1986.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Whalen is credited for an "unparalleled cycle of commercial investment and development" in Albany due to his "aggressive business development programs".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Prior to the recession of the 1990s, downtown Albany was home to four Fortune 500 companies.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] After the death of Corning and the retirement of Congressman Sam Stratton, the political environment changed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Long-term office holders became rare in the 1980s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Local media began following the drama surrounding county politics (specifically that of the newly created county executive position); the loss of Corning (and eventually the machine) led to a lack of interest in city politics.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The election of Gerald Jennings was a surprise, and he served as mayor from 1994 until his retirement at the end of 2013.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] His tenure essentially ended the political machine that had been in place since the 1920s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Many state workers were relocated from the Harriman State Office Campus to downtown, helping its retail businesses and vitality.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw a real possibility for a long-discussed and controversial Albany Convention Center; it opened in 2017 with the goal of making Albany a viable location for large events hosted by statewide organizations.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany remains an important location for business presence, given its role as de facto seat of Tech Valley and being home to the state capitol.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Fortune 500 companies with offices in Albany include American Express, J.P.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Morgan and Chase, Merrill Lynch, General Electric, Verizon, Goldman Sachs, International Paper, and Key Bank.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany won the All-America City Award in both 1991 and 2009.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] is located at the extreme right of the image.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is about 135 miles (217 km) north of New York City on the Hudson River.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It has a total area of 21.8 square miles (56 km2), of which 21.4 square miles (55 km2) is land and 0.4 square miles (1.0 km2) (1.8%) is water.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The city is bordered on the north by the town of Colonie (along with the village of Menands), on the west by the town of Guilderland, and on the south by the town of Bethlehem.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The former Foxes Creek, Beaver Kill, and Rutten Kill were diverted underground in the 19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] There are four lakes within city limits: Buckingham Lake; Rensselaer Lake at the mouth of the Patroon Creek; Tivoli Lake, which was formed as a reservoir and once connected to the Patroon Creek; and Washington Park Lake, which was formed by damming the Beaver Kill.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The highest natural point in Albany is a USGS benchmark near the Loudonville Reservoir off Birch Hill Road, at 378 feet (115 m) above sea level.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The lowest point is at the Hudson River—which is still technically an estuary at Albany and is affected by the Atlantic tide—at an average of 2 feet (0.61 m) above sea level at low tide and 4 feet (1.2 m) at high tide.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The interior of Albany consists of rolling hills which were once part of the Albany Pine Bush, an area of pitch pine and scrub oak, and has arid, sandy soil that is a remnant of the ancient Lake Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Due to development, the Pine Bush has shrunk from an original 25,000 to 6,000 acres (10,100 to 2,400 ha) today.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] A preserve was set up by the State Legislature in 1988 and is on the city's western edge, spilling into Guilderland and Colonie; it is the only sizable inland pine barrens sand dune ecosystem in the United States, and is home to many endangered species, including the Karner Blue butterfly.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in the humid continental climate zone (Köppen climate classification: Dfa), and features cold, snowy winters, and hot, humid summers; the city experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in plant hardiness zone 6a near downtown and along the shore of the Hudson and 5b at its western end.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany receives 40.7 inches (1,030 mm) of precipitation per year, with 138 days of at least 0.01 in (0.25 mm) of precipitation each year.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Snowfall is significant, totaling 59.4 inches (151 cm) per season, but with less accumulation than the lake effect areas to the north and west, as it is farther from Lake Ontario.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] However, Albany is close enough to the Atlantic coast to receive heavy snow from Nor'easters and the city occasionally receives Alberta clippers.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Winters can be very cold with fluctuating conditions; temperatures drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below on nine nights per annum.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Summers in Albany can contain stretches of excessive heat and humidity, with temperatures of 90 °F (32 °C) or hotter on nine days per year.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the variety of its communities, Albany is often called a "city of neighborhoods." The neighborhoods of Albany include Arbor Hill; Center Square, "[an] eclectic mix of residential and commercial [buildings], including bars, night clubs, restaurants, and stores"; Pine Hills; and the South End.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Historically, Albany's population has been mixed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] First dominated by Mohican and Mohawk people, then Dutch and Germans, it was overtaken by the British in the early 19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Irish immigrants soon outnumbered most other ethnicities by the mid-19th century, and were followed by Italians and Poles.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the mid-to-late 20th century, the African-American population increased with thousands of people from the rural South, as part of the Great Migration.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Until after the Revolution, Albany's population consisted mostly of ethnic Dutch descendants.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Settlers migrating from New England tipped the balance toward British ethnicity in the early 19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Jobs on the turnpikes, canals, and railroads attracted floods of Irish immigrants in the early 19th century, especially in the 1840s during the Great Famine, solidifying the city's Irish base.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Michael Nolan became Albany's first Irish Catholic mayor in 1878, two years before Boston.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Polish and Italian immigrants began arriving in Albany in the wave of immigration in the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Their numbers were smaller than in many other eastern cities mainly because most had found manufacturing jobs at General Electric in Schenectady.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Jewish community had been established early, with Sephardic Jewish members as part of the Beverwijck community.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Its population rose during the late 19th century, when many Ashkenazi Jews immigrated from eastern Europe.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In that period, there was also an influx of Chinese and east Asian immigrants, who settled in the downtown section of the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Many of their descendants have since moved to suburban areas.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Asian immigration all but halted after the Immigration Act of 1924.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany saw its last large immigration pattern as part of the Great Migration when many African Americans moved there from the American South before and after World War I to fill industrial positions and find other opportunities.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In the early years, African-Americans lived together with Italians, Jews, and other immigrants in the South End, where housing was older and less expensive.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The black community has grown as a proportion of the population since then; African Americans made up three percent of the city's population in 1950, six percent in 1960, 12 percent in 1970, and 30 percent in 2010.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The change in proportion is related mostly to middle-class white families moving to the suburbs and black families remaining within city limits during the same time period.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2007, the number of Burmese refugees to Albany has increased.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Burmese refugee community consists mostly of people of Karen ethnicity.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] An estimated 5,000 Burmese refugees reside in Albany as of January 2015.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Like most cities of comparable age and size, Albany has well-established Orthodox Christian, Roman Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish communities.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to the oldest Christian congregation in Upstate New York and the Mother Churches of two Christian dioceses.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of June 2010, eight churches or religious buildings in the city were listed on the National Register of Historic Places, one of which—St.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Peter's Episcopal Church on State Street—is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Established in 1642, the congregation of the First Church in Albany (Reformed), also known as the North Dutch Church (on North Pearl Street), is the second-oldest Reformed Church in America.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2023, the city was home to twelve Catholic churches and four Episcopal churches.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Despite its history of Christendom, in 2019 the Albany-Schenectady-Troy MSA was found to be among the most post-Christian cities in the United States in a study by Christian polling firm The Barna Group.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] A significant Jewish presence has existed in Albany as early as 1658.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2010, Albany is home to two Conservative synagogues, a Chabad-Lubavitch synagogue, an Orthodox synagogue, and two Reform synagogues.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is also home to one of the few Karaite synagogues outside Israel.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2008, the total membership in Albany's synagogues was estimated at 12,000–13,000, with half the members residing outside the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Since the early 2000s, there has been an increase in Orthodox Jews moving to Albany from the New York Metro area, largely due to cheaper housing prices and closer walking proximity to synagogues.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Islamic community in Albany and its surrounding suburbs is represented by at least four major mosques in the region.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The Muslim population increased substantially starting in the late 2000s, with the arrival of many refugees from countries such as Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Exact numbers on religious denominations in Albany are not readily available.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Demographic statistics in the United States depend heavily on the United States Census Bureau, which cannot ask about religious affiliation as part of its decennial census.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] It does compile some national and statewide religious statistics, but these are not representative of a city the size of Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] One report from 2000 offers religious affiliations for Albany County.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] According to the data, 59.2% of Albany County residents identified as Christian: 47% are Roman Catholic, 8.4% are mainline Protestants, 2.7% are Evangelical Protestants, and 1.1% are Eastern or Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Residents who practice Judaism make up 4.2% of the population and Muslims represent 0.2%.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2020 census, Albany had a population of 99,224.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] There were 42,158 households in Albany, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Of all households, 22.4% were married-couple households, 29.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] There were 48,031 housing units, of which 12.2% were vacant.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the Latino population was: 4.57% Puerto Rican, 1.45% Dominican, .84% Ecuadorian, .77% Mexican, .69% Salvadoran, .22% Cuban.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, Albany's population density was 4,572.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,765.5/km2).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] There were 46,362 housing units at an average density of 2,166.4 per square mile (836.5/km2); 5,205 of these units (11.2%) were vacant.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 52.3% white; 27% Black or African American; 0.06% Native American or Native Alaskan; 7.4% Asian; 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; .06% from other races; and 3.6% from two or more races.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] A total of 9.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 52.0% of the population in 2010, compared to 87.0% in 1970.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 90.6 males.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.5 males.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Some 81.3% of the population had completed high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 census, the top five ancestry groups in the city were African American (27%), Irish (18.1%), Italian (12.4%), German (10.4%), and English (5.2%); (33.1%) of the population reported "other ancestries".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to a Triqui language-speaking community of Mexican-Americans.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] There were 40,709 households in Albany in 2000, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 25.3% were married couples living together, 16.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.8% were non-families.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] 41.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.95.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The median income for a household in the city in 2000 was $96,713, and the median income for a family was $100,374 (male, year-round worker) and $91,052 (female, year-round worker).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the city was $73,985.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] About 16.0% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 12.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The rate of reported violent crimes for 2008 (1,095 incidents per 100,000 residents) were more than double the rate for similarly sized US cities.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Reported property crimes (4,669 incidents per 100,000 residents) were somewhat lower.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] With a 2013 Census-estimated population of 1.1 million, the eight county Capital District, encompassing Albany, Troy, Schenectady and Saratoga, is the third-most populous metropolitan region in the state.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Demographically speaking, the population of Albany and the Capital District mirrors the characteristics of the United States consumer population as a whole better than any other major municipality in the country.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] According to a 2004 study conducted by the Acxiom Corporation, Albany and its environs are the top-ranked standard test market for new business and retail products.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse all scored within the top five.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's violent crime rate was 10.03 per 1,000 residents in 2023, compared to 7.69 in Buffalo, 7.39 in Rochester, 8.22 in Syracuse, and 7.72 in New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] New York State had statewide violent crime rate of 3.90 per 1,000 people in 2023.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's economy, along with that of the Capital District in general, is heavily dependent on government, health care, education, and more recently, technology.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Because of these typically steady economic bases, the local economy has been relatively immune to national economic recessions in the past.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 2009, more than 25 percent of the city's population worked in government-related positions.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's estimated daytime population is more than 162,000.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Companies based in Albany include Trans World Entertainment, AMRI Global and Clough Harbour.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] In 2019, Albany had the fourth-highest amount of lawyers in its employment pool (7.5 lawyers per 1,000 jobs) compared to the rest of the nation, behind Washington, D.C., Trenton, New Jersey, and New York City, respectively.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Since the 2000s, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward high technology, a growing fourth sector of the area's economic base.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] Tech Valley is a marketing name for the eastern part of New York State, encompassing Albany, the Capital District, and the Hudson Valley.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] The area's high technology ecosystem is supported by technologically focused academic institutions including Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the State University of New York Polytechnic Institute.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p01] A notable video game development cluster has grown in and around Albany starting in the 2010s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's geographic situation—roughly equidistant from New York City to the south and Montreal to the north—makes it a convenient stop for nationally touring artists and acts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Palace Theatre and The Egg are mid-sized forums for music, theater, and spoken-word performances; the Capital Repertory Theatre is smaller.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The MVP Arena is the city's largest musical venue for nationally and internationally prominent bands.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] It also hosts trade shows, sporting events, and other large gatherings.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In recent years, the city's government has invested resources to cultivate venues and neighborhoods that attract after-hours business.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Madison Avenue, Pearl Street, Delaware Avenue and Lark Street are the most active entertainment areas in the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Many restaurants, clubs, and bars have opened since the mid-1990s, revitalizing areas that had once been abandoned and reclaiming old row houses, businesses, and a pump station.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Much of the bar restaurant scene features classic Irish Pubs.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Price Chopper Fabulous Fourth and Fireworks Festival at the Empire State Plaza celebrates Independence Day with musical performances and the region's largest fireworks display.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Chefs' Food & Wine Festival donates all net proceeds to deserving Albany Arts Organizations and is held the Thursday-Saturday preceding Martin Luther King Weekend.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Because of Albany's historical and political significance, the city has numerous museums, historical buildings, and historic districts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to the New York State Museum, the New York State Library and the New York State Archives; all three facilities are in the Cultural Education Center at the south end of Empire State Plaza and are free to the public.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The USS *Slater* (DE-766), a decommissioned World War II destroyer escort that was restored in 1998, is a museum ship docked in the Hudson River at Quay Street.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] It is the only ship of its kind still afloat.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center, at the corner of Clinton Avenue and Broadway at Quackenbush Square, hosts a museum, gift shop, and the Henry Hudson Planetarium.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In early 2012, the Irish American Heritage Museum opened in downtown Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The museum is home to exhibits highlighting the contributions of the Irish people in America.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to 57 listings on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and five National Historic Landmarks.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Ten Broeck Mansion, a 1797 Federal-style mansion (later renovated in the Greek-Revival style) built for Abraham Ten Broeck (mayor of Albany 1779–1783 and 1796–1798) is a historic house museum and the headquarters of the Albany County Historical Association; it was added to the NRHP in 1971.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Later known as "Arbor Hill", it gave the current neighborhood its name.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has been the subject, inspiration, or location for many written and cinematic works.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Many non-fiction works have been written on the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] One of the city's more notable claims to fame is *Ironweed* (1983), the 1984 Pulitzer Prize-winning book by Albany native William Kennedy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] *Ironweed* was the third in a series of books by Kennedy known as the "Albany Cycle".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The elusive author Trevanian also grew up in Albany and wrote *The Crazyladies of Pearl Street* (2005), about a North Albany neighborhood along Pearl Street.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The book is considered a semi-autobiographical memoir.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 1987, the film version of *Ironweed* premiered at the Palace Theatre.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The movie starred Jack Nicholson and Meryl Streep, each of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances; much of the filming was done on location in Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Most recently the downtown area was the site of filming for the action-thriller *Salt*, starring Angelina Jolie, and the action-comedy *The Other Guys*, starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Authors Herman Melville and Henry James lived with their families in Albany when young, before their careers.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] James identified his character Isabel Archer, the heroine of his novel *The Portrait of a Lady*, as being from Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Gregory Maguire, author of *Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West* (adapted for the Broadway hit *Wicked*), grew up in North Albany and graduated from SUNY Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Empire State Plaza, a collection of state agency office buildings, dominates almost any view of Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Built between 1965 and 1978 at the hand of Governor Nelson A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Rockefeller and architect Wallace Harrison, the complex is a powerful example of late American modern architecture and remains a controversial building project both for displacing city residents and for its architectural style.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The most recognizable aspect of the complex is the Erastus Corning Tower, the tallest building in New York outside of New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Juxtaposed at the north end of the Plaza is the 19th-century New York State Capitol, the seat of the New York State Legislature and the home of the Governor's office.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's initial architecture incorporated many Dutch influences, followed soon after by those of the English.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Quackenbush House, a Dutch Colonial brick mansion, was built c.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] 1736; Schuyler Mansion, a Georgian-style mansion, was built in 1765; and the oldest building in Albany is the 1728 Van Ostrande-Radliff House at 48 Hudson Avenue.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's housing varies greatly, with mostly row houses in the older sections of town, closer to the river.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Housing type quickly changes as one travels westward, beginning with two-family homes of the late 19th century, and one-family homes built after World War II in the western end of the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall, designed by Henry Hobson Richardson, was opened in 1883.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Capitol was opened in 1899 (after 32 years of construction) at a cost of $25 million, making it the most expensive government building at the time.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's Union Station, a major Beaux-Arts design, was under construction at the same time; it opened in 1900.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 1912, the Beaux-Arts styled New York State Department of Education Building opened on Washington Avenue near the Capitol.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] It has a classical exterior, which features a block-long white marble colonnade.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The 1920s brought the Art Deco movement, which is illustrated by the Home Savings Bank Building (1927) on North Pearl Street and the Alfred E.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Smith Building (1930) on South Swan Street, two of Albany's tallest high-rises.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Architecture from the 1960s and 1970s is well represented in the city, especially at the W.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus (1950s and 1960s) and on the uptown campus of the University at Albany (1962–1971).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The state office campus was planned in the 1950s by governor W.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman to offer more parking and easier access for state employees.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The uptown SUNY campus was built in the 1960s under Governor Rockefeller on the site of the city-owned Albany Country Club.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Straying from the popular open campus layout, SUNY Albany has a centralized building layout with administrative and classroom buildings at center surrounded by four student housing towers.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The design called for much use of concrete and glass, and the style has slender, round-topped columns and pillars reminiscent of those at Lincoln Center in New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Downtown has seen a revival in recent decades, often considered to have begun with Norstar Bank's renovation of the former Union Station as its corporate headquarters in 1986.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Knickerbocker Arena (MVP Arena) was originally slated for suburban Colonie, but was instead built downtown and opened in 1990.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has teams in two top-level professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada (New York Atlas, and Albany Firebirds), and several minor-league sports teams with varying levels of support.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils were a minor league ice hockey team that moved to the city for the 2010–11 season.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] They played in the American Hockey League and were affiliated with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Devils replaced the Albany River Rats, who played in the Capital Region from 1990 to 2010, when they relocated to Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils moved to Binghamton, New York in 2017.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Times Union Center has previously hosted arena football teams including the Albany Firebirds in the Arena Football League (AFL) from 1990 to 2000 and then a team originally known as the Albany Conquest and later the Firebirds in the af2, the AFL's developmental league, from 2002 to 2009.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Empire played in the AFL from 2018 through the 2019 season when the league folded.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] A new Albany Empire was relaunched in the National Arena League for the 2021 season.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, Antonio Brown bought the team; after a series of problems with payments and personnel, the NAL suspended the franchise in the middle of the 2023 season.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] A relaunched Albany Firebirds franchise began playing in 2024.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Tri-City ValleyCats short season minor league baseball team have played at the Joseph L.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Bruno Stadium on the Hudson Valley Community College campus in North Greenbush since 2002.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to the ValleyCats' arrival, the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs (1995–2002) played at Heritage Park in Colonie; due to financial pressures, and facing impending competition from the ValleyCats, the franchise folded in 2002.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Legends (International Basketball League), played in the Washington Avenue Armory from 2010 to 2014 before moving to Schenectady.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Patroons have played at the Armory on and off since 1982 and currently play in The Basketball League.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] With the large number of local colleges and universities around Albany, college sports are popular.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The University at Albany's Great Danes play at the Division I level in all sports.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The football team is a member of the Coastal Athletic Association while all other sports teams play as members of the America East Conference.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2006, UAlbany became the first SUNY-affiliated school to send a team to the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Siena Saints saw a rise in popularity after their men's basketball team made it to the NCAA Tournament in 2008, 2009, and 2010.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] All 18 Saints teams are Division I and play in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Although Siena's campus is in nearby Colonie, the men's basketball team plays at the Times Union Center.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] UAlbany hosted the New York Giants training camp from 1996 to 2012.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] On February 23, 2021, it was announced that the National Lacrosse League (NLL) would return to the city with the relocation of the New England Black Wolves.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The team was named the Albany FireWolves on April 15, 2021.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] This is the second NLL team to be based in the area; the first, the Albany Attack, played in the city from 2000 to 2003.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, the Premier Lacrosse League (PLL) selected cities for their 8 franchises, and Albany was chosen as the primary home for the New York Atlas.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2024, the Albany Firebirds began playing in the AFL at the MVP Arena.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] After one season in the AFL, the team moved to the AF1.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The 518 Ballers (American Basketball Association) have played at Our Savior's Christian School since 2023.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has more than 60 public parks and recreation areas.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was organized as the Middle Public Square in 1806.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Its current location has been public property since the *Dongan Charter* of 1686 gave the city title to all property not privately owned.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was designed by John Bogart and John Cuyler in 1870, and opened for public use the following year.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The original lake house, designed by Frederick W.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The park had previously been used as a cemetery; its graves were moved to Albany Rural Cemetery.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park is a popular place to exercise and play sports; skate during the winter; people-watch during Tulip Fest; and attend plays at the amphitheater during the summer.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Other parks in Albany include Lincoln Park, Buckingham Park, the Corning Preserve, the Albany Skyway and the Pine Bush.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Lincoln Park, southwest of the Empire State Plaza, was organized in 1886 and was originally known as Beaver Park.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Today, the park has a pool that is open during the summer months.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Buckingham Lake Park is between Manning Boulevard and Route 85 in the Buckingham Pond neighborhood; it contains a pond with fountains, a footpath, a playground, and picnic tables.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Riverfront Park at the Corning Preserve has an 800-seat amphitheatre that hosts events in non-winter months, most notably the *Alive at 5* summer concert series.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Preserve's visitors center details the ecology of the Hudson River and the local environment.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The park has a bike trail and boat launch and was effectively separated from downtown by Interstate 787 until the opening of the Hudson River Way in 2002.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Other public parks include Westland Hill Park, Hoffman Park, Beverwyck Park, and Liberty Park, today a small circular grassy patch in downtown on Hudson Avenue, which is Albany's oldest park.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Ridgefield Park is home to the clay courts of the Albany Tennis Club, one of the oldest tennis clubs in the United States.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The municipal golf course, New Course at Albany, was constructed in 1929 as the Albany Municipal Golf Course, later renamed the Capital Hills at Albany, and remodeled in 1991.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has a strong mayor-council government, which functions under the Dongan Charter, granted by colonial governor Thomas Dongan in 1686 when Albany was incorporated.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] A revised charter was adopted by referendum in 1998, but was legally reckoned as an amendment to the Dongan Charter.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] This gives Albany the distinction of having the oldest active city charter in the United States and "arguably the longest-running instrument of municipal government in the Western Hemisphere." The mayor, who is elected every four years, heads the executive branch of city government.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The current mayor, Kathy Sheehan, was first elected in 2013.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Common Council represents the legislative branch of city government and is made up of fifteen council members (each elected from one ward) and an at-large Common Council President.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The current president is Corey Ellis; he began his term in January 2018.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] While Albany has its own city government, it has also been the seat of Albany County since the county's formation in 1683 and the capital of New York since 1797.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] As such, the city is home to all branches of the county and state governments, as well as its own.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall sits on Eagle Street, opposite the State Capitol, and the Albany County Office Building is on State Street.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The state government has offices scattered throughout the city.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is in the 20th Congressional district, represented by Paul Tonko (D) in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The city is represented by Chuck Schumer (D) and Kirsten Gillibrand (D) in the United States Senate.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] On the state level, the city is in the 44th district in the New York Senate, represented by Patricia Fahy (D).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In the New York Assembly, western Albany is in the 109th district, represented by Gabriella Romero (D) while downtown and eastern Albany are in the 108th district, represented by John T.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] As the seat of Albany County, the city is the location of the county's courts including Family Court, County Court, Surrogate Court, Supreme Court, and New York Court of Appeals.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is the site of a federal courthouse that houses the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's politics have been dominated by the Democratic Party since the 1920s; Daniel (Uncle Dan) O'Connell established a political machine in the city with the election of William Stormont Hackett as mayor in 1922.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to that, William Barnes Jr. had set up a Republican machine in the 1890s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Barnes' success is attributed to the fact that he owned two newspapers in Albany and that he was the grandson of Thurlow Weed, the influential newspaper publisher and political boss.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] O'Connell's organization overcame Barnes' in 1922 and survived well into the 1980s (even after his death).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In many instances, votes were outright bought.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Gerald Jennings' upset in the 1993 Democratic mayoral primary over Harold Joyce, who had the Democratic Party's formal endorsement and had only recently been its county chairman, is often cited as the end of the O'Connell era in Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In the early 21st century, Albany continued to be dominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Democratic Party enrollment in the city was 38,862 in 2009, while Republican enrollment was 3,487.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2022, every elected city position had been held by a Democrat since 1931.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In November 2013, Kathy Sheehan became the first woman to be elected Mayor of Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The City School District of Albany (CSDA) operates the city's public school system, which consists of 17 schools and learning centers; in addition, there are 7 charter schools, including Green Tech Charter High School, and Albany Leadership High School.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In the 2015–2016 school year, over 9,000 students were enrolled in the public school system.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The district had an average class size of 18, an 81-percent graduation rate, and a 5-percent dropout rate.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Although considered by the state to be one of the lowest-achieving high schools in New York, Albany High was listed as the nation's 976th best high school in a 2010 *Newsweek/Washington Post* report.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany also has a number of private schools, including the coed Bishop Maginn High School and Albany Free School; the all-boys Albany Academy; and the all-girls Academy of the Holy Names and Albany Academy for Girls.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Medical College (private), today part of Albany Medical Center, was founded in 1839.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany Law School (private) is the oldest law school in New York and the fourth-oldest in the country; it was opened in 1851.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] President William McKinley was an alumnus.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences (private) is the second-oldest pharmacy school in New York and the fifteenth-oldest in the United States.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Normal School, one of the oldest teachers colleges in the United States, opened in 1844; it was later known as the State Teachers College.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] It eventually evolved into the University at Albany, also known as SUNY Albany (public), which inherited the Normal School's original downtown campus on Western Avenue.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The center of the campus moved to its current Uptown Campus in the west end of the city in 1970.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] SUNY Albany is a unit of the State University of New York and one of only four university centers in the system.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Other colleges and universities in Albany include Empire State College, The College of Saint Rose, Excelsior College, Maria College, Mildred Elley, and Sage College of Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Nearby Hudson Valley Community College (HVCC) fills the community college niche in the Albany-Troy area.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The effect of the campuses on the city's population is substantial: Combining the student bodies of all the aforementioned campuses (except HVCC) results in 63,149 students, or almost 70 percent of the 2008 estimate of Albany's permanent population.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The *Times Union* is Albany's primary daily newspaper and the only one based close to the city; its headquarters moved from within city limits to suburban Colonie in the 1960s after a dispute with Mayor Corning over land needed for expansion.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Its circulation totals about 73,000 on weekdays and 143,000 on Sundays.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Serving Albany to a lesser degree are *The Daily Gazette*, based in Schenectady, and *The Record*, of Troy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] *Metroland* is the alternative newsweekly in the area, publishing each Thursday, while *The Business Review* is a business weekly published each Friday.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The *Legislative Gazette*, another weekly newspaper, focuses exclusively on issues related to the Legislature and the state government.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2010, the Albany-Schenectady-Troy media market is the 63rd-largest in the country in terms of radio and the 57th-largest in terms of television audiences.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] It is a broadcast market with historical significance.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The pioneering influence of General Electric in Schenectady directly contributed to the area emerging as the birthplace of station-based television with WRGB; the station was also the first affiliate of NBC.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 1947, the region was home to the first independently owned and operated commercial FM radio station in the United States: W47A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] WGY was the second commercial radio station in New York and the twelfth in the nation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District is home to ABC affiliate WTEN 10, CBS affiliate WRGB 6 (also operating CW affiliate WCWN 45), Fox affiliate WXXA 23, NBC affiliate WNYT 13 (also operating MyNetworkTV affiliate WNYA 51), and PBS member station WMHT 17.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Charter Communications hosts Spectrum News Capital Region, the area's only local 24-hour news channel.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Thruway is the most prominent highway serving Albany.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] From Albany westward, it is part of Interstate 90, connecting Albany with major cities such as Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] To the south, it becomes part of Interstate 87 and leads to New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] A short un-tolled section of Interstate 90 extends around the northern and eastern portions of Albany before linking back up with the Berkshire extension of the Thruway, which leads to the Massachusetts Turnpike and ultimately to Boston.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] North of Albany, Interstate 87 follows the Northway to Canada at Champlain; Autoroute 15 continues into Quebec, linking Albany to Montreal.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Interstate 787 links downtown Albany to the southbound I-87/Thruway to the south, while to the north, it links with the free portion of Interstate 90 before continuing to Troy, Watervliet, Colonie, and Menands.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] By way of Route 7, I-787 connects to the Northway.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Since the closure of Union Station on Broadway, area passenger-rail service is provided by Amtrak at the Albany-Rensselaer station across the river in Rensselaer.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2009, the station saw more than 720,000 passengers, making it Amtrak's second-busiest in New York, behind Manhattan's Penn Station.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Amtrak provides service south to New York City; north to Montreal, and Burlington (Vermont); west to Niagara Falls, Toronto and Chicago; and east to Boston.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's major airport is Albany International Airport in Colonie.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Major airline service to Albany includes service by: American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, JetBlue Airways, and United Airlines; Million Air is the local fixed-base operator.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] In 2010, Albany had the highest average airfare in New York, though the per-mile cost on its busiest routes was second-lowest in the state.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District Transportation Authority (CDTA) provides bus service throughout Albany and the surrounding area, including Schenectady, Troy, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The city was once served by an urban streetcar service maintained by the United Traction Company.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] As in many American cities, after the advent of the automobile, light rail services declined in Albany and were replaced by bus and taxi services.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Greyhound Lines, Trailways, Peter Pan, Short Line, Vermont Translines, and Yankee Trails buses all serve a downtown terminal.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Low-cost curbside bus service from the SUNY Albany campus and the Rensselaer station is also provided by Megabus, with direct service to New York City.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Albany, long an important Hudson River port, today serves domestic and international ships and barges through the Port of Albany-Rensselaer, on both sides of the river.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The port has the largest mobile harbor crane in the state of New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Barge Canal, the ultimate successor of the Erie Canal, is in use today, largely by tourist and private boats.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] The city of Nijmegen, Netherlands connected with Albany following World War II.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] With the help of the Catholic university in Albany, the Catholic University of Nijmegen (Radboud University Nijmegen) rebuilt its partly destroyed library, with over 50,000 books being donated to the Dutch university.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] To show its gratitude for post-war assistance, the city sent Albany 50,000 tulip bulbs in 1948; this act led to the establishment of the annual Tulip Festival.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albany-new-york-p02] Most of the other connections were made in the 1980s during Mayor Whalen's term in office as part of his cultural expansion program.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was born in Philadelphia, the son of Richard Bache, Jr., and Sophia Burrell Dallas Bache.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He came from a family prominent in American politics.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He was the nephew of Vice-President George M.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Dallas, the grandson of Secretary of the Treasury Alexander Dallas, and the great-grandson of Benjamin Franklin.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] After graduating from the United States Military Academy at West Point in 1825, as first in his class, he was an assistant professor of engineering there for some time.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] As a second lieutenant in the United States Army Corps of Engineers, he was engaged in the construction of Fort Adams in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache resigned from the Army on June 1, 1829.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache was a professor of natural philosophy and chemistry at the University of Pennsylvania from 1828 to 1841 and again from 1842 to 1843.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He spent 1836–1838 in Europe on behalf of the trustees of what became Girard College; he was named president of the college after his return.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Abroad, he examined European education systems, and on his return he published a valuable report.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] From 1839 to 1842, he served as the first president of Central High School of Philadelphia, one of the oldest public high schools in the United States.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1843, on the death of Professor Ferdinand Rudolph Hassler, Bache was appointed superintendent of the United States Coast Survey.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Whereas Hassler had faced continual doubts from Congress, Bache succeeded in convincing legislators of the value of geodesy in addition to geomagnetic and meteorological research.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] With many contacts, friends, and family among the nation's political and military leaders, Bache won liberal appropriations to build up his agency and greatly expand its work.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] By the mid 1850s it had become the federal government's leading scientific bureau.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1849, it began study of the Pacific Coast, which the US had newly acquired via the US-Mexico War and Oregon Treaty.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Assisted by Isaac Stevens, his number two in Washington, DC, Bache reorganized the Coast Survey so that it could complete initial mapping of the entire US coast.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] By the 1840s, a clique of leading US scientists began to coalesce around Bache with the goal of professionalizing their fields.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] They formalized with establishment of the Association of American Geologists and Naturalists in 1843 (renamed the American Association for the Advancement of Science five years later) and the Smithsonian Institution in 1846.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Informally, Bache and his circle called themselves the Scientific Lazzaroni.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Together, the groups created and enforced standards of intellectual merit with the goal of elevating the nation and its reputation.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] This meant discrediting charlatans but, at times, also denying research funding or academic appointments to others.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Perhaps most important, the groups advised and even mentored politicians and army engineers.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache would lead the AAAS until 1851 and serve on the Smithsonian's board of regents throughout his term as Coast Survey superintendent.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] In 1863, amid the demands of the Civil War, Bache was a central figure in the establishment of the National Academy of Sciences, created by an act of Congress to provide scientific advice to the federal government.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He was elected its first president and served in that role until his death in 1867.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] As the sectional crisis worsened through the late 1850s, Coast Survey budgets became ensnared by polarization and conflicts in Congress.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Then, the start of war in 1861 brought a stop to work along the South's Atlantic and Gulf coasts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Bache withdrew Survey ships from the region so they would not fall into secessionists' hands.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] At the same time, some staff resigned to join the Confederacy.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] A number of trusted friends and Democratic allies, including senators Jefferson Davis and Stephen Mallory, would lead the rebellion — acts that Bache took as both political and personal treachery.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Yet the Civil War enhanced the Coast Survey's stature in Washington, D.C.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] By this time, the agency had amassed charts of southern harbors, rivers, and coastal terrain.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] The research gave a critical advantage to the Union navy and army.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Meanwhile, Bache continued to lead scientists to greater influence in government, helping to establish the U.S.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He also played a central role in the founding of the National Academy of Sciences in 1863 and served as its first president.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] Official duties and private worries contributed to Bache's declining health.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] By 1864 he had suffered a stroke, which left him handicapped and unable to work without his wife's assistance.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] At the time of his death, he had served as head of the Coast Survey for 24 years.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] After the Civil War, Bache was elected a 3rd Class Companion of the Military Order of the Loyal Legion of the United States (MOLLUS) in consideration of his contributions to the war effort.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He married Nancy Clark Fowler on September 30, 1838, in Newport, Rhode Island.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] She was born in Newport and died on January 13, 1870, in Philadelphia.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] She assisted in the publication of much of his work.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] They adopted one son, Henry Wood Bache (1839–1878).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He died at Newport, Rhode Island on February 17, 1867, from cerebral softening.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexander-dallas-bache] He was buried in the Congressional Cemetery in Washington, D.C., under a monument designed by architect Henry Hobson Richardson.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Caswell was professor of mathematics and natural philosophy at Brown University from 1828 to 1850, and of mathematics and astronomy from 1850 to 1864.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Professor Caswell was president of Brown University from 1868 to 1872.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] He was one of the founders of the American Association for the Advancement of Science and served as its President in 1857.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Besides several papers on meteorology in the *Reports of the Smithsonian Institution*, he wrote *The Life of Francis Wayland*, a *Textbook on Astronomy*, and a *Memorial of John Barstow* (1864).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Caswell was the son of Samuel (1760–1851) and Polly Foster Seaver Caswell (1768–1818).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Through his father, he is a direct descendant of Peregrine White, the first baby boy born aboard the Mayflower while it was anchored at the Massachusetts harbor.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] On May 17, 1830, Caswell married Esther Lois Thompson (September 1, 1802 – June 25, 1850) of Providence, the daughter of Edward Kinnicutt Thompson and his wife, Sarah Kuhn Swope/Swoope Thompson.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] She was a 3rd great-granddaughter of Roger Kinnicutt, who was born in England and emigrated to America around 1635.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] After Esther's death, Caswell married Elizabeth Brown Edmands (1817–1880) in 1855.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] His notable descendants include James Rowland Angell, Alexis C.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/alexis-caswell] Angell, Robert Cooley Angell, and Constance Green.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He was born in Boston, Massachusetts, the son of Lucretia Dana (Goddard) and Benjamin Apthorp Gould, the principal of Boston Latin School, which the younger Gould attended.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The poet Hannah Flagg Gould was his aunt.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied at Harvard College under Benjamin Peirce, graduating in 1844.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied mathematics and astronomy under C.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gauss at Göttingen, Germany, during which time he published approximately 20 papers on the observation and motion of comets and asteroids.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] (he was the first American to receive this degree in astronomy) he toured European observatories asking for advice on what could be done to further astronomy as a professional science in the U.S.A.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The main advice he received was to start a professional journal modeled after what was then the world's leading astronomical publication, the *Astronomische Nachrichten*.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould returned to America in 1848 and from 1852 to 1867 worked in the United States Coast Survey, where he worked in geodetic astronomy and was in charge of the longitude department.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He developed and organized the service, was one of the first to determine longitudes by telegraphic means, and employed the Atlantic cable in 1866 to establish accurate longitude-relations between Europe and America.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] One of his assistants and life-long mentee was Seth Carlo Chandler, who went on to discover the Chandler wobble.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] After his return to Cambridge, Massachusetts, Gould started the *Astronomical Journal* in 1849, which he published until 1861.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He resumed publication in 1885 and it is still published today.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] From 1855 to 1859 he acted as director of the Dudley Observatory at Albany, New York, and in 1859 published a discussion of the places and proper motions of circumpolar stars to be used as standards by the United States Coast Survey.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1861 he undertook the enormous task of preparing for publication the records of astronomical observations made at the United States Naval Observatory since 1850.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1851 Gould suggested numbering asteroids in their order of discovery, and placing this number in a disk (circle) as the generic symbol of an asteroid.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] That same year, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he was admitted to the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati to represent his grandfather Captain Benjamin Gould.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In the 1890s he became an early member of the Massachusetts Society of the Sons of the American Revolution.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Appointed in 1862 actuary to the United States Sanitary Commission, he issued in 1869 an important volume of *Investigations in the Military and Anthropological Statistics of American Soldiers*.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] This study, informed by Gould's commitment to race science, purported to construct typologies of Black and Indigenous bodies, in particular.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he fitted up a private observatory at Cambridge, Massachusetts, and undertook in 1868, on behalf of the Argentine republic, to organize a national observatory at Córdoba.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1871 he became the first director of the Argentine National Observatory (today, Observatorio Astronómico de Córdoba of the National University of Córdoba).
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] While there, he and four assistants (including Miles Rock) extensively mapped the southern hemisphere skies using newly developed photometric methods.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] On June 1, 1884, he made the last definite sighting of the Great Comet of 1882.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The need of astronomers for good weather prediction spurred Gould to collaborate with Argentine colleagues to develop the Argentine National Weather Service, the first in South America.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Rutherfurd's photographs of the Pleiades in 1866 entitle him to rank as a pioneer in the use of the camera as an instrument of precision; and he secured at Córdoba 1400 negatives of southern star clusters, the reduction of which occupied the closing years of his life.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He remained in Argentina until 1885, when he returned to Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He received the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1883 and the James Craig Watson Medal in 1887.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Astronomers continue to investigate the astrophysics of a large scale feature of the Milky Way to which he called their attention in 1877, and honor him with its name, The Gould Belt.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] A crater on the Moon is named after him.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1892.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He died at Cambridge, Massachusetts in 1896.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1874, while in Argentina with his assistants, Gould completed his greatest work, the *Uranometria Argentina*, consisting of an atlas published in 1877 and catalog in 1879, for which he received in 1883 the gold medal of the Royal Astronomical Society.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The atlas introduced the system of defining constellation boundaries along lines of right ascension and declination, which was officially adopted by the International Astronomical Union for the whole sky in 1930.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The catalog assigned Gould designations to all bright stars within 100 degrees of the south celestial pole in a manner similar to what Flamsteed had earlier done for the northern hemisphere.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] An updated version, to which late 20th century data have been appended to the complete information for all stars in the original Uranometria Argentina, is available at www.uranometriaargentina.com/.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould followed his *Uranometria Argentina* with a zone-catalogue of 73,160 stars (1884), and a general catalogue (1885) compiled from meridian observations of 32,448 stars.
[src:benjamin-apthorp-gould/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Alice Bache Gould (1868–1953), a mathematician, philanthropist, and historian, was one of his five children.
